Haghog's Handy Guide to Adding in 3d Models for Artifacts to CK3
(Credit to El Tyranos Youtube Video which explained this process - much of this is a written adaptation of said video. If you get lost following this guide, check the video out here - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZqXxbS0cRsM&t=2052s)

-This guide assumes you have some experience with 3d modelling, or have been able to find a 3d model from a website such as Sketchfab. 
-In order to follow this guide you will need:
	-Blender
		-3D modelling program (you should probably know what that is prior to reading this if you want to follow along with this guide)
			-Other alternatives exist. I do not have experience with them so will not discuss them here
		-Blender Plugins
			-PDX Blender Tools: available at https://github.com/ross-g/io_pdx_mesh/
				-This will allow you to import/export models from CK3 and into CK3. It is essential for this process.
	-Substance Painter
		-Adobe Program for texturing. This is a paid program (though it does have a free trial). 
		-There are potentially other programs to use, and you may be able Blender for texturing, but Substance Painter is most straightforward for this process
			-Substance Painter Addons
				-Owlcoholic's CK3 Substance Painter settings: availabe at https://drive.google.com/file/d/1k9Yi7Ry136iyTsloRyTupg2UgHPlA7Wi/view
					-This will allow you to export textures correctly for CK3. You can do this manually, but it is much, much easier to use these presets
	Paint.net (or another image editor that can convert to .dds files)
-Make sure you have these add-ons in your program prior to starting this process!

Stage One: Importing a mesh for a Court Artifact into CK3

	1 - Import mesh into Blender and resize if needed
		-In Layout View, you will have a menu called PDX Blender Tools (resize the panel if needed). Make sure you are familiar with this for this process
		-It can be difficult to judge the scale of a mesh in Blender by itself; I recommend importing a vanilla artifact mesh as a size comparison
			-This can be done by selecting "Load Mesh" in PDX Blender Tools, and navigating to the steamapps\common\Crusader Kings III\game\gfx\models\ folder
				-Searching through the folders there should provide you with a range of in-game models to compare your own to.

	2 - UV unwrap your model
		-In the UV Editing tab, make a new image in the left window, saving as a UV grid.
		-Select your entire mesh, and select UV from the top menu.
			-Select Unwrap in here and examine the image created on your left
				-The flatter the image, the better quality the UV map is. Dense sections of overlapping lines is a bad sign, and will likely cause issues when trying to model your object in Substance Painter 
					-I unfortunately am not good at fixing UV models; discuss this with the CK3 Mod Coop for further information on fixing UV maps.

	3 - Apply a PDX material to your mesh
		-In the layout tab, select your mesh and click "Create" under "PDX materials" in PDX Blender Tools
			-In the pop-up box that appears
				-Name your texture; it should be "PDXmat_your_model_nameShape" or something similar; the PDXmat and Shape parts are important for the texturing to work later on (Especially the Shape part!)
				-Choose your material type; for a court artifact, PdxMeshStandard works
				-Check the box for "Apply material to selected"
		-You should see the named material appear on your object in the Scene Collection - the name will appear next to a red patchy sphere icon
		-You must also rename your mesh (the green inverted triangle above the red sphere) to "your_model_nameShape" at this point; not doing this will break your model in-game

	4 - Export your model as a FBX model for Substance Painter
		-I recommend you choose "Limit to Selected Objects" on the right of the box that opens up, and make sure that you only have your model selected
		-If you change your model from this point, you will need to re-export your FBX model for Substance Painter.

	5 - Export your model to your CK3 mod
		-Click "Save mesh" in PDX Blender Tools and save to the relevant folder for your artifact
			-Make sure to select "Selected Only" in the export options, and make sure that you only have your model selected

	6 - Texture your model in Substance Painter
		-Import your model into Substance Painter
		-Select the croissant icon at the top and bake your model (you may want to watch a video around this process)
		-Texture your model until you are happy with it
			-I recommend taking some time to experiment with materials and alphas around this; YouTube is a good place for information on this

	6.5 - Apply predefined textures to your model (Optional)
		-This step is needed if your model has textures already provided (such as a Sketchfab download)
		-Import your textures into Substance Painer
		-Select the Texture Set Settings tab
			-Apply your normal map texture as the normal map for the object
		-Add a fill layer to your model
			-In the fill layer, apply your Base Color, Roughness and Metallic textures to the model
		-You should have your textures applied at this point, ready for the next step.


	7 - Export CK3 textures in Substance Painter
		-In the settings box for this, select CK3_standard as the output template
		-Make sure you are exporting this textures to the correct folder
		-You may want to increase the size of your textures to at least 2048.

	8 - Convert these texture files into .dds files
		-I use paint.net as its free and works for this
		-Convert your files to .dds, save them in the folder you saved your model in, and name them
			-A naming scheme like "your_model_name_xxx" works well for this
				-In place of the xxx, put the relevant texture type: Diffuse, Normal and Properties
			-When saving these files, choose from the options provided:
				-Diffuse: BC1 (Linear, DXT1) with Generate Mipmaps ticked
				-Normal: BC3 (Linear, DXT5) with Generate Mipmaps ticked
				-Properties: BC3 (Linear, DXT5) with Generate Mipmaps ticked

	9 - Set up the .asset file for your model
		-Copy an .asset file from another artifact and clear out the code inside. Rename the file to your_model_name.asset
			-(You can simply rename the code inside, but you must know what you're doing)
			-Fill out the code, using the below example as a model:
				pdxmesh = {
					name = "your_model_name_mesh"
					file = "your_model_name.mesh"

					meshsettings = {
						name = "your_model_nameShape"
						index = 0
						texture_diffuse = "your_model_name_diffuse.dds"
						texture_normal = "your_model_name_normal.dds"
						texture_specular = "your_model_name_properties.dds"
						shader = "court"
						shader_file = "gfx/FX/court_scene.shader"
					}
				}

				entity = {
					name = "your_model_name_entity"
					pdxmesh = "your_model_name_mesh"
				}
			-To step through
				-The pdxmesh calls the file name, which will have the Shape name inside the mesh
				-The meshsettings will refer to the textures you have created
				-The entity calls on the defined pdxmesh, which you have defined above it.

	10 - Follow steps 1 - 6 of my Artifact Tutorial (in ate_artifact_steps.info)
		-One key point: on Step 3
			-Define the artifact's visuals, and refer to your model's entity you have defined in your .asset file
			-For example, in the visuals file:
				your_model = {
					icon = "model_icon.dds"
					asset = your_model_name_entity
				}

	11 - Test in-game!
		-The model should be working and visible in-game.

